In TypeScript, you can define the types of a value using interfaces. The standard interfaces are `string`, `number`, `boolean`, and `any`. These interfaces are usually used to prevent taking in invalid or incorrect input.

For example, you could define the input of a user for an interface that accepts `string` and `number` as values. With this definition, you would not force the user into an error if they input `null` or another invalid input.

```ts
interface UserInput {
    name: string;
    age: number;
}
```

This code is interpreted as if the user accepts the value `name` as a `string` and the value `age` as a `number`. Therefore, it is prohibited to force the user to take in an incorrect input.

Alternatively, you can define the types of a value using the keyword convention. This convention allows you to create your own interface that is derived from other interfaces. This enables you to define any combination of types for a value without explicitly specifying the individual types.

For example, you could define a field in an interface that accepts the input of a user and accepts any input. With this definition, you would not force the user into an error if they input an invalid value.

```ts
interface UserInput {
    any: any;
}
```

This code is interpreted as if the user accepts any input, but only as types `string` and `number`. Therefore, it is prohibited to force the user to take in an incorrect input.

